Prologue
"Please!" Queen Elwynn pleaded, "Do not send her away! She is just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with royal advisors standing beside him. The queen had given birth to a girl. The mere thought of it made the Ice King frown.
The baby girl looked like her mother: light blue eyes, snow-white hair interspersed with a few strands of blue. The Ice King believed that having a daughter would make him appear weak. After all, he only had sons before this.
You have two choices, either kill this child or abandon her in the wilderness. Elwynn, this is your punishment," he spat out her name as if it were poison, as he always did.
The Frostland was not always a kingdom. It had been divided into two parts in the north and south. The northern part became a non-magical kingdom, while the southern part was a realm filled with fantastical power. Due to the greed of the north, the two realms were engaged in ceaseless warfare until the south proposed a truce.
At that time, the Southern Kingdom was already in despair. The royal family was willing to do anything to prevent the bloody conflict. They proposed to marry their only princess to the Northern Prince, becoming the Queen of the North and giving birth to a son as the future king. Afterwards, the Southern and Northern kingdoms would be unified under one rule. The Northern kingdom accepted the proposal, and Princess Elwynn was thus married to Prince Akul.
"Please, My King, for my child's safety, you can do anything to me. Lock me up, exiled me, even kill me," Queen Elwynn pleaded, holding her child tightly.
The Ice King lowered his gaze at the queen, his eyes brimming with disgust. Maybe, just maybe, he would show her a bit of pity. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, caring for him when he was at his lowest, and bearing his children.
"Alright. The child can live in the palace." Upon hearing the Ice King's words, the queen breathed a sigh of relief. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisors and Queen Elwynn exchanged terrified glances. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. "As you wish, My King," she bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisors to bring Queen Elwynn's daughter to an empty room in Alwen's palace. Afterward, he commanded the soldiers to take her to the execution ground where all the citizens could see.
When the soldiers escorted her to the execution ground, the citizens saw their only queen—the kindest of them all—who was about to be executed, and they felt furious. Some cried, some shouted to try to attack the soldiers, and others wondered why this was happening; but they all shared the same question.
"Release her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Queen Elwynn approached the stake, the most terrifying figure in the kingdom emerged. He was the executioner for the burning. Queen Alwen, the former queen, would be burned alive. No one should be executed by fire, not even criminals. In the Frostland, burning was the cruelest form of punishment.
Aelwen was bound to a stake, and the king began to recount how Queen Elwynn had betrayed them all. The people of the Frostland refused to believe and would never accept the king’s words. Then, the executioner lit the stake, and a tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
“Carly, live!” Aelwen’s life as queen came to an end.
The hall was silent.
In the southern wing of the icy palace, a never-ending “click” came from the room on the far left. Servants who passed by always wondered what was inside but were too afraid to get close. Maids scurried through the hall, whispering and spreading rumors. Some believed that the late King Ice’s wife, Aelwen, was kept in this room, waiting to be freed.
They were very wrong. Averie thought as she walked towards the southern wing, servants walking back and forth along the walls and whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there were also many rumors about who "TA" was, because "TA" was the only person allowed to enter the room.
Knocking gently on the door, Avery whispered, "Miss Carly, are you in there?" Standing before this complex door adorned with patterns of snowflakes and crowns, which were symbols of the royal family, Avery spoke softly.
She wasn't sure if she would really be allowed to enter this time, unlike before. I still have bruises from last time. Avery recalled the incident and couldn't help but laugh. At that moment, Carly had thrown a book at him, but when she realized it was him, she immediately apologized.
A soft sound came from inside the room, seemingly saying that she could nowhere else go and was stuck there.
"Can I come in?" Avery asked, remembering the consequences of his unauthorized entry last time.
Another soft sound came from inside the room, seeming to say, "Come in." Avery felt a chill, not sure if it was from the cold or from the voice. Despite having spent many years there, Avery still found it strange to hear a voice from within the room.
"I'm coming in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. By normal standards, the sight inside the room was unusual, but it was also expected. The room was filled with papers. Books were scattered everywhere, the table was broken, and there were numerous ice sculptures. There were no windows, and hardly any light. It was also colder here than in other parts of the palace (which explained a lot). The room looked as though it had been hit by a blizzard, everything was messy and disorganized.
The girl in the room was curled up in bed, wrapped in blankets, reading from a notebook. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Avery asked, sitting by Carlie's bedside.
